@article{Kagan2015,
abstract = {N anometre-scale colloidal crystals of group II–VI, III–V and IV–VI semiconductors are prized for their size-dependent optical and electronic properties that emerge as the exci-ton, electron and hole are quantum-confined in the 2–20 nm regime 1,2 . Hence, these crystals are known as quantum dots (QDs) or nanocrystals. As colloids, QDs may be dispersed in solvents and assembled using low-cost, large-area, solution-based tech-niques to form solid-state materials. Akin to the construction of atomic solids from atoms, the creation of QD solids from semi-conductor QD building blocks is dictated by the composition, size and shape of the QDs and their spacing and organization in the solid. In atomic solids, as the interatomic separation between atoms decreases, the electronic wavefunctions of the isolated atomic states increasingly overlap, thus forming extended states in amorphous semiconductors and delocalized bands in crystalline semiconduc-tors. Analogously, in QD solids, as the interdot spacing decreases, the interaction between the electronic wavefunctions of the QDs increases, producing cooperative physical phenomena that are unique to the QD solid. These QD solids may be locally ordered glasses or long-range-ordered QD superlattices or supercrystals. The first evidence of electronic communication between QDs in solids was the observation of fluorescence resonance energy trans-fer, the radiationless transfer of excitations that is possible through electromagnetic interactions between the transition dipoles of neighbouring QDs at larger 1–2 nm interdot spacings 3 . Early studies also demonstrated photo-4 , electrochemical-5 and electrostatically induced 6 charge transport. However, recent methods to decrease the interdot separation further via ligand stripping, exchange or decomposition, and also to dope and passivate the QD surface, are driving the evolution from low-mobility ({\textless}1 cm 2 V –1 s –1) hop-ping transport through localized electronic states to high-mobility ({\textgreater}10 cm 2 V –1 s –1) band-like transport in extended electronic states of QD solids 7–14 . The strength of coupling between QDs in solids can be continuously controlled, thereby allowing us to harness new combinations of optical, electrical, thermal and mechanical prop-erties in QD solids that are not found in natural materials systems. The combination of high-mobility charge transport and solution-based deposition of QD solids is spurring the design of these mate-rials for electronic, optoelectronic and thermoelectric devices. Here we review the synthesis, assembly, ligand treatments and doping of QDs and their solids that have been explored Charge transport in strongly coupled quantum dot solids},
