or various systems, 10 and are tabulated in a recent review. 11 While much research has focused on the FT, the Kawasaki function 12 ͗exp(Ϫ⍀ t)͘, which is intimately related to the FT, has rarely been discussed. A proof by Evans and Searles 13 shows that the Kawasaki function obeys the iden-tity ͗exp͑Ϫ⍀ t ͒͘ϵ1. ͑3͒ We call this equation the Kawasaki Identity ͑KI͒. In this paper we show that the KI is a direct result of the FT and that the Kawasaki function is a useful diagnostic tool. The devia-tion of the Kawasaki function from unity provides an imme-diate indicator to the effectiveness of the phase-space sam-pling and to the quality of the results. First we show that the KI follows directly from the FT, Eq. ͑1͒, and the definition of an ensemble average. The en-semble average of the Kawasaki function can be written as ͗exp͑Ϫ⍀ t ͒͘ϭ ͵},
