@article{Pertot2014,
abstract = {This Letter comprises an experimental and theoretical investigation of the time evolution of a Fermi gas following fast and slow quenches of a one-dimensional optical double-well superlattice potential. We investigate both the local tunneling in the connected double wells and the global dynamics towards a steady state, i.e., a time-independent state. The local observables in the steady state resemble those of a thermal equilibrium state, whereas the global properties indicate a strong nonequilibrium situation. One of the grand goals of physics is the dynamic control of quantum matter. Inducing controlled changes between quantum states, both rapid and slow, has important appli-cations in quantum computing, quantum devices, and the dynamic control of materials as, for example, ultrafast demagnetization and magnetization control. The demand for the dynamic control of quantum matter raises many fundamental questions on the understanding of nonequili-brium quantum processes. Recently, the dynamic behavior of a system as a response to so-called quantum quenches, sudden or slow parameter changes, has attracted particular interest. Part of the increased interest stems from the experimental progress in the area of atomic quantum gases, which are excellent systems to study quantum dynamics [1,2]. This is due to the clean preparation, wide tunability, and long coherence times. In particular, different dynamical proc-esses can be well separated and time scales for the real-time detection are experimentally favorable. The fastest relevant energy scale, the Fermi energy, is on the order of 10 kHz and can be well resolved. So far, experimental progress in probing and understanding dynamical phenomena in opti-cal lattices has been mostly focused on bosonic systems where, for example, interaction quenches have been studied [3–12]. With fermionic gases in optical lattices, interaction quenches [13–16] and spin dynamics have been inves-tigated [17,18]. In this Letter we investigate experimentally and theo-retically the time evolution of a Fermi gas in a bichromatic optical lattice which is imposed along one dimension of the gas, following a sudden or a slow quench of the lattice potential. We initially prepare a patterned density distribu-tion and measure the relaxation of both local and nonlocal observables towards a steady state. Experimentally [19], we start from a noninteracting degenerate gas of N ¼ 1.2ð2Þ × 10 5 40 K atoms in two spin states in a dipole trap with trapping frequencies $\omega$ x ¼ 2$\pi$ × 38 Hz, $\omega$ y ¼ 2$\pi$ × 66 Hz, and $\omega$ z ¼ 2$\pi$ × 376 Hz. The scattering length between the two components is set to zero by means of a Feshbach resonance. The gas has a temperature of ð0.3 AE 0.1ÞT F where k B T F ¼ E F is the Fermi energy. We then apply a bichromatic optical lattice along the x axis which consists of a short-period (" green ") lattice of wavelength $\lambda$ G ¼ 532 nm and a long-period (" red ") lattice of wavelength $\lambda$ R ¼ 1064 nm [20]. The bichromatic lattice potential at the location of the atoms is given by VðxÞ ¼ V G cos 2 ðk G x − ϕÞ − V R cos 2 ðk R xÞ, where V G (V R) is the potential depth of the green (red) lattice and k R=G ¼ 2$\pi$=$\lambda$ R=G . The periods of the two lattices differ by a factor of 2, up to a small, controlled and adjustable difference. This difference results in the relative phase ϕ and permits the generation of distinct double-well configurations [5]. We use this control over the lattice potential for a density-patterned loading of the atomic ensemble and for the subsequent discrimination of the density in even and odd wells during measurement [4,5,21]. The ramp sequence for the optical lattice potentials and the resulting lowest eigenenergies of the central double wells are sketched in Figs. 1(a) and 1(b). The Fermi gas is initially loaded into the red lattice by ramping up the depth to V R ¼ 48E rec;R in 50 ms, where E rec;R=G ¼ ℏ},
